In general you cannot perform this sort of reversing. In functional categories language, you have two functors between the following categories:

    T --&gt; Stream&lt;T&gt;
    Stream&lt;T&gt; --&gt; CompletableFuture&lt;Stream&lt;T&gt;&gt;

You simply do not have a functor between

    T --&gt; CompletableFuture&lt;T&gt;
    CompletableFuture&lt;T&gt; --&gt; Stream&lt;CompletableFuture&lt;T&gt;&gt;

If you don&#39;t want to care about the outer `CompletableFuture` and need `Stream` semantic, you need some sort of `StreamT` [monad transfomer][1]. Java currently do not have higher-kinded types support, so I&#39;m not sure (but maybe applying some non-standard tricks) it is possible to implement something like `StreamT`


  [1]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monad_transformer

If I don&#39;t misunderstand your intention, you want to flatten the result only. you can use the `Spliterator` to receive result lazily &amp; use `flatMap` to merge `Stream`s into a flatten stream, for example:

    Stream&lt;CompletableFuture&lt;ScrappingResult&gt;&gt; scrappingFuturesUnwrapped =
                   scrappingFutures.flatMap(each -&gt; unwrap(each));


---

    static &lt;T&gt; Stream&lt;? extends CompletableFuture&lt;T&gt;&gt; 
      unwrap(CompletableFuture&lt;? extends List&lt;? extends T&gt;&gt; master) {

        return generate(new Predicate&lt;Consumer&lt;? super CompletableFuture&lt;T&gt;&gt;&gt;() {

            private Iterator&lt;? extends T&gt; cursor;

            @Override
            public boolean test(Consumer&lt;? super CompletableFuture&lt;T&gt;&gt; consumer) {
                cursor = cursor == null ? await().iterator() : cursor;
                if (cursor.hasNext()) {
                    consumer.accept(completedFuture(cursor.next()));
                    return true;
                }
                return false;
            }

            //                        v--- blocked at the first time
            private List&lt;? extends T&gt; await() {
                try {
                    return master.get();
                } catch (InterruptedException | ExecutionException e) {
                    throw new CompletionException(e);
                }
            }
        });
    }

    static &lt;T&gt; Stream&lt;? extends CompletableFuture&lt;T&gt;&gt; 
      generate(Predicate&lt;Consumer&lt;? super CompletableFuture&lt;T&gt;&gt;&gt; generator) {

        long unknownSize = Long.MAX_VALUE;
        return stream(new AbstractSpliterator&lt;CompletableFuture&lt;T&gt;&gt;(unknownSize, 0) {
            public boolean tryAdvance(Consumer&lt;? super CompletableFuture&lt;T&gt;&gt; action) {
                return generator.test(action);
            }
        }, false);
    }


## Summary 

The solution above is just my first thought and it isn&#39;t the best approach in this case, you can think it against with [big design first][1]. However, even if it is a poor solution but I&#39;ll keep it here since it maybe give somebody thinking in other ways. for more details, you can see the comments of @Holger from here and [there](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/48561183/replace-for-loop-with-java-8-foreach-for-updating-values/48561991?noredirect=1#comment84126733_48561991).

I admit the best approach is what @Holger have said below, since there is no one write it down, please let me record it to serve more people.

    Stream&lt;CompletableFuture&lt;ScrappingResult&gt;&gt; scrappingFuturesUnwrapped =
                   scrappingFutures.flatMap(each -&gt; each.join().stream())
                                   .map(CompletableFuture::completedFuture);


[1]: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Big_Design_Up_Front

You can convert a `Stream&lt;CompletableFuture&lt;T&gt;&gt;` to a `CompletableFuture&lt;Stream&lt;T&gt;&gt;` using [`Stream.reduce`][1]:

    static &lt;T&gt; CompletableFuture&lt;Stream&lt;T&gt;&gt; reduce(Stream&lt;CompletableFuture&lt;T&gt;&gt; futures) {
        return futures
            .map(future -&gt; future.thenApply(Stream::of))
            .reduce(
                CompletableFuture.completedFuture(Stream.empty()),
                MyClass::combine);
    }

For this to work, we still need to define a helper function `combine` for combining two instances of `CompletableFuture&lt;Stream&lt;T&gt;&gt;` that concatenates the stream inside of the individual futures:

    static &lt;T&gt;CompletableFuture&lt;Stream&lt;T&gt;&gt; combine(CompletableFuture&lt;Stream&lt;T&gt;&gt; future1, CompletableFuture&lt;Stream&lt;T&gt;&gt; future2) {
        return future1
            .thenCompose(stream1 -&gt; future2
            .thenApply(stream2 -&gt; Stream.concat(stream1, stream2)));
    }


  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/11/docs/api/java.base/java/util/stream/Stream.html#reduce(T,java.util.function.BinaryOperator)

[michid](https://stackoverflow.com/users/402428/michid)&#39;s answer works and is the most purely functional, but it&#39;s a bit inefficient because it creates a &quot;linked list&quot; of nested concatenated singleton streams, something like this:
```
concat(of(A),
       concat(of(B),
              concat(of(C), ...)))
```

So, here&#39;s a more efficient (albeit not purely functional) version, which only requires the creation of a single intermediate array of all the futures:
```
static &lt;T&gt; CompletableFuture&lt;Stream&lt;T&gt;&gt; allOfStream(Stream&lt;CompletableFuture&lt;T&gt;&gt; stream) {
  CompletableFuture&lt;T&gt;[] futuresArray = futures.&lt;CompletableFuture&lt;T&gt;&gt;toArray(CompletableFuture[]::new);
  return CompletableFuture.allOf(futuresArray)
    .thenApply(ignored -&gt; Arrays.stream(futuresArray).map(CompletableFuture::join));
}
```
This is still non-blocking, since the lambda in `thenApply` will only be invoked if all the futures in `allOf` succeeded, and so the `join` call on each future will also return immediately - it will effectively just be an &quot;unwrap&quot; operation from `CompletableFuture&lt;T&gt;` to `T`.

But it is eager, ie it won&#39;t work on infinite streams, since `toArray` will never terminate. I&#39;m not sure what the behavior would be of the purely functional answer for infinite streams.

